segments.text: They worked well together.
And then when she got, I believe it was Dr. Williams, she called me and said, I just don't think I can work for him.
And I said, yes, you can.
You can work for anybody.
She didn't know him that well, and she was just out of her element.
So, of course, it worked out beautifully.
I think he sent her a dozen roses, and I think he realized she was having time adjusting too, but it all worked out really well.
Describe Dr. Williams as you remember him.
Well, of course, I didn't have a lot of connection with him, so I can't really comment on it, so I don't really know.
What do you think was the general campus impression of him?
I don't know.
Oh, you don't?
I'm sorry, I really don't.
We had all we could handle in the graduate college, and I really didn't.
Do you know what the student nickname for him was?
No.
Smiling Jack.
Oh, well.
Because he was always upbeat.
Yeah.
Okay.
No, I really have no... Not long after Dr. Williams got here, he appointed John Calhoun as the vice president.
Dr. Coonsey remained as the graduate dean.
And you all moved to the Teague building.
Yes.
Then he retired.
He who?
Couldn't say.
Leo Berner, was he the?
Leo Berner was the associate dean.
Okay.
And then we had two or three sometimes assistant deans that handled all the paperwork.
They signed off on the paperwork before it went into the computer.
So we still had paperwork.
By that time were you the senior staff person?
I was the administrative secretary.
Right.
And who did you have?
How many people did you have helping you?
We had about 10 in there.
If we can count the thesis part, which he was a part of it also.
But we had to.
We had that, we had, I'm sorry, I can't remember the enrollment and graduate programs, but we were graduating 200 or 300 each graduation, and there was a lot of paperwork.
And then we were trying to get a,
a program that would get rid of the dead wood, because we needed the space so the filing cabinets were full.
That was always a constant battle on records and where to put them and everything.
But it worked well.
Dr. Kunze was good.
And then when Dr. Kunze retired and Dr. Berner took over, he pretty much went along the same path as Dr. Kunze had established.
Describe Leo Berner.
Leo Burner is a sweetheart.
He's a nice person.
He's easygoing.
He doesn't like any problems or troubles or anything to upset the apple cart, so we kept things running pretty smooth.
I don't think he made any great progress, but he also didn't lose anything either.
Dr. Kunze's background was agronomy and soils.
Leo Burner's was oceanography, biological oceanography.
Did, in the routine of what they liked or didn't like, what was the differences between those two?
I'd rather not comment.
Okay, all right.
Okay.
I have bitter memories about it.
The, let's see, was it, at what point did you all start wearing pantsuits?
Was it under Berner or Coonsy?
No, no, no, it was under Dr. Coonsy in the Coke building.
How did y'all make the request of him?
How did y'all raise the question?
We just started talking among ourselves, you know, do you think we could wear pantsuits?
Well, we can just ask.
So we got together, two or three of us, especially the pretty girls in the office, they always could get whatever they wanted.
But no, it was not a problem because it was coming and they could see it.
Did you all use many student employees?
We used a lot of student wives.
That was part of the problem in that office.
All the jobs were low-scale, dead-end jobs.
So there was turnover.
A lot of turnover.
The student wives were excellent.
We got real good help with the student wives.
But it was...
We couldn't keep anybody who was very good if they were staying because there was no place for them to go to advance.
So we had to fight for, they always thought the graduate college spent too much money, so at least Dr. Kunze said that.
And so our budgets were very trim.
He trimmed, he was that kind of a man, he trimmed everything to the bare bones.
we had to start putting in for better positions in that office in order to maintain it.
During the years that Calhoun was the vice president, was there any difference in the routine?
No, Dr. Calhoun was very, he was good to all of us.
I mean, most of them were afraid of Dr. Calhoun, but he was...
He was very good.
He let Dr. Kunze do, I mean, they got together on certain things if there was a problem, but they had no problem working together.
As far as y'all were aware, where were the chief academic decisions made?
The academic decisions in the graduate office was made through the graduate council.
And one of the things that,
what Rutter wanted Dr. Kunze to do was put some structure in the graduate catalog.
It was too flexible, and it was being used flexibly, you know, depending on who asks.
Now, who was on the Graduate Council?
Who made up the Graduate Council?
I can't tell you, but... Was it faculty or deans?
They were representatives of the different colleges.
They weren't always the deans and not necessarily the deans.
And Kunze presided over it, didn't he?
He was the chairman.
And when the deans... And then it went to the Academic Programs Committee from the Graduate College.
So he started building structure into the graduate catalogs that we could live with and use so we could... And the deans met weekly, APC, Academic Programs Council, or whatever that stood for.
Yeah.
And...
Then where did the decision come from to... Do away with the deans?
Yeah, do away with the dean of the graduate school.
We're really not sure.
I mean, I'm not sure.
But I think several of the colleges, and I would say engineering might be one of them, college of business might be another one, that wanted to run their own shows.
And they were growing, too.
They were growing big time, and they wanted to do their own things.
Now, this was in the 80s?
This was in the 80s.
I believe Dr. Kunze retired in 84, Dr. Berner in 87, so this is... After that.
88 and 89, we were without a dean.
It became a director.
They made a director.
Dr. Gussman became the director.
And he was on the graduate council.
That was the best thing that happened for me in those two years was when he became director because I could work with Dr. Gussman because he knew what we were doing and everything.
I don't know anything about him.
Describe him.
Larry Gussman was a lovable, energetic...
fun kind of person.
He's a mathematician.
He worked for NASA.
G-U-S-E-M-A-N.
He was well-respected.
I mean, he did a lot of graduate work in the mathematics or the College of Science.
And so he was well prepared to be the director when he, and he was my suggestion to the boss when he asked me who I would want as director.
I told him, Gusman, and that's who got it.
I was shocked, but I was pleased, too.
But he'd made it in life different.
And then when I retired, they hired a man to take my job, and in two years, both those men were dead.
Dr. Gusman died, and the man that took my place died.
Now, you retired what year?
So I took it two years, one year without anybody in the office.
And so then the graduate programs in each of the colleges were run by the dean of that college.
Well, they still come through the graduate office, but there was no authority particularly in the graduate office.
But the paperwork still flowed in.
It never quit.
But the authority...
The authority was pretty much established in the colleges.
Now, if they wanted a new degree program, they still had to submit paperwork for one to be approved through the channels, but they had pretty much to say what they...
Which do you think was, in hindsight, which do you think was the better system?
I only saw it from my point of view, so I can't say for the second one, but I thought it was more
It was a stronger program when there was an umbrella overlooking the whole scene.
I agree with you.
And it's like they said, once you let the toothpaste out of the tube, you can never put it back.
And we were told that from other schools that had tried that, and it didn't work.
Now I understand there is a dean there in the graduate office now, but I'm not sure what kind of power he had.
But it was, I felt like that,
what we had, what Dr. Coonsey had worked so hard to structure and have it overall a good package was now coming loose at the end.
But see, that's from my standpoint.
I can't speak from theirs.
All right.
In your 25 years, which presidents, I'm not going to ask the negative, to which presidents would you give the highest marks for their leadership of Texas A&M?
I'd have to say Rutter simply because I know what he did for us.
I don't know about any other.
I just was too isolated in the graduate programs to speak for the university.
Which of the vice presidents for academic affairs would you give the, now we call it provost, but in those days vice, to which would you give the?
I think Dr. Calhoun was the one that was most beneficial for us.
I agree with you.
Why?
On what do you base your opinion?
I agree.
I just know how he supported us, and he was watching over things.
He was not somebody that just let things go by without him.
But he was watching to see what happened, and if he had some criticism of it, well, he always spoke up, and Dr. Kunze always worked it out.
So I felt like we had his support, and yet he let Dr. Kunze do the job he was supposed to do.
Now, the next question has to do with the point of view of you as a staff member.
When the Board of Regents recreated the system after Dr. Williams had his heart attack, they made him chancellor and recreated the separate position of president.
He recommended Dr. Calhoun for that position, but the board selected Jarvis Miller.
Do you remember in the Teague building, do you remember what was it like for you and the other staff members?
What changes were there?
As far as we were concerned, we were still doing the same thing we were doing before, so it really didn't affect us any.
As far as it affecting the dean, it may have, but he didn't talk about it.
The staff people, the sad thing about the staff is that we weren't paid enough.
We worked hard, but we really didn't have a good salary ever.
And were there merit increases for staff in those days?
The few merit increases you had were dealt, the dean or, yes, the dean would be the one to designate who got it.
which really wasn't always fair.
I think there was more, there were more problems with the fact that we were underpaid and overworked.
Most of those offices that we would talk to don't have enough to do.
We had more than we could do.
And we worked hard and I worked hard and I expect everybody else to work hard.
It made me a pretty bitter woman.
I mean, bitter, but I was just, that's all I did was work.
During those years, what was the busiest time of the year?
The busiest time of the year was in the springtime.
All of those awards had to be made.
A lot of the preparations for fall had to be made, the fellowships.

the awards, the graduate student awards, association of former students awards, all of those things came and we were pretty much in charge of getting the applications and getting them ready to be reviewed and that kind of thing.
So I think spring was the hardest.
Summer wasn't easy, but spring was hard.
And of the colleges,
Again, not going to ask the negative.
Which colleges, from the point of view of the graduate school, which colleges did the best job from your... From my standpoint?
Mm-hmm.
Who managed their responsibilities best?
I think agriculture did.
Or at least they were
They tried to work within the system, and if there was a problem, then they'd just pick up the phone and we'd talk about it.
But they weren't fighting it.
In other words, they were just trying to do what we had established.
And I think the agriculture did the best job.
Were there some deans that you enjoyed most?
Well, let me think of who the deans were.
The best deans to work with?
I'd have to think about that one.
Of course, I did work through their administrative secretaries, so it was not easy for me to say that, because any time we had anything to communicate, it was through the secretary.
Which of those secretaries were the best to work with?
Oh, I liked them all, let's face it.
Mayor Ruth Patronella, she was always pleasant to work with.
In agriculture?
In agriculture.
And Betty Robinson in science.
And Peggy Ritchie in liberal arts.
Yeah, those are people that, like I said, we never had any problem asking for help or giving help to each other, so it worked out.
I'm not trying to paint this beautiful picture, but it was a beautiful picture to work during those years.
Do you remember, from the point of view of the graduate office, do you remember any outside interference from beyond the campus ever attempted?
Did any regent or former student or politician ever attempt to get somebody graduated or admitted or?
Not flunked out or anything?
I really can't remember any incident.
If it happened, then it was kept.
I'm not aware of any.
I mean, I don't, I just don't know of any.
It was pretty straightforward.
Either they passed their oral or they didn't pass their oral or they didn't have the GPR.
It was, you know, pretty cut and dried.
So there wasn't a lot of flexibility.
Now, as far as extensions on deadlines, we gave a lot of them.
But that's okay.
If we can get somebody graduating and give them a little more time, that's fine.
And we had no problem with giving those things.
And they usually worked out fine.
Now that extension on deadline meant that they had to have their thesis turned or dissertation by a certain date and sometimes that could be extended for them.

Well those were not easy to give because there was so much work to be done with those things that we couldn't be a lot, very flexible but we're talking about if they wanted to take their prelim beyond the
time that they're supposed to have it, like an extension, or graduate maybe a semester later or something like that, that was easy to give.
In dealing with the registrar and director of admissions office, compare H.L.
Heaton to Ed Cooper.
Of course, when I knew Mr. Heaton, I was working for Mr. Perriman, and
I didn't have a lot of interaction with Mr. Eaton.
He was always strolling around the office looking at what we were doing and very pleasant.
Ed Cooper, the people I worked with under Ed Cooper were super.
By the way, our present registrar, Don Carter, used to be our graduate assistant.
That reminds me, yes.
Describe him as a graduate assistant.
Oh, Don was fun.
He was a very good graduate assistant, but he was lots of fun, and he loved to tease Mrs. Watson, and she loved it in spite of her saying she didn't.
She loved that.
But Don could clean up the storeroom, the closet, with all the supplies in, to perfection, and that's the way he wanted it.
Mm-hmm.

I used to leave a drawer out behind me where I had some forms in it and there was a passageway and Don got very upset with me because he was going to fall and break his neck on that drawer if I didn't close it.
But it was a good time.
Don Carter was a splendid student worker.
One of the best.
About what was the continuous staff?
About how many people did you all have?
In the early days, we had about five.
I think that would about cover it.
Admissions and bookkeeper, receptionist and a typist, the administrative secretary.
That's about all we had.
Then in the later days, what, 15?
Well, they actually saved about 10.
I'll have to stop and think about that.
Of course, we used a lot of student help as much as possible, which without it we couldn't have handled.
And don't I remember part of the time in the Teague building there were people with desks out in the hallway?
In the hallway, yes.
And then we had offices down the hall.
When they added a recruiter,
Jack Ivins came in and they made him a recruiter.
He took up some offices and he had an assistant that was working with him.
And I guess that's the only office we had down the hall.
But we just had filing cabinets every nook and cranny.
As you think about all those, that quarter century, what were some of the happiest times, the high points?
The high points.
Most enjoyable.
Christmas parties.
Where were they held?
Well, Dr. Kunze would always have his at his house.
And I was trying to think, Dr. Hall had it, where do we have it?
I think we had it at his house, too.
And then we had it at Werner's home.
But it was fun when we got away from the office and could socialize together.
When we weren't working, that was a good time.
Other high points?
Of course, we had, I can't say for the graduate college high points.
It was just when personal people we'd worked with got married or had children or something like that.
That was always nice, and we always gave them parties.
Was it also a feel-good event when you'd finally sent off all of that commencement's dissertation and thesis lists and everything to the registrar?
I would like to say it was, but the only problem with that is I had everything stacked up waiting for me to work on the next graduation that had backed up while I was finishing that one.
So it was just a continuous process.
It was good to be through and have those lists turned in, yes.
Now, y'all never had any catastrophe, no fire, no... No.
No, where everything went wrong.

No, I found that during the Christmas holidays, I would always pick up the mail and open it and bring it up to the office, and two times I found the office flooded because the pipes had burst and the floors were under water, but no damage to the equipment, just water damage.
our experiences with the new automated typing equipment.
Yes, talk about that.
Of course it was a wonderful thing except that the equipment we got to begin with was not good and we would try it and keep trying it and have them in and everything.
It was more frustrating than anything.
But finally we were able to get some really good word processing equipment which made our lives much easier and
was the answer to it.
And of course we went into the computers.
Everybody had their own computer and we had our own software that we worked into.
Certain people would do certain things and that was good.
Make believe that someone didn't know the dimensions of the building.
About how big was the data processing center when it first opened?
How big was a building?
It was big.
It was very big.
And also when we asked for reports
we would have to get them in batches.
And if there was something wrong with the report, there were batches of paper that had to be trashed.
We tried to use it as scrap paper, but we couldn't use that much paper.
But we'd have to run, because that was the economical time to run that was a certain time of the evening.
And of course, we had to go down and pick up our reports at the Data Processing Center, bring them up, look at them.
trial and error, they finally got straightened out.
But it was a great system.
Right now, as you were getting ready to conclude, have we left out anything that you can think of, any important topics?
Not that I can think of at the moment.
I probably will when I go home.
I think of a lot of things.
Well, we can put that in when we get the typed version.
Well, I just remember my last two years was so difficult because
All of a sudden, there were no deans, and the associate provost for research and graduate studies was across campus.
We moved all the excess filing cabinets out of the dean's offices into the hall, and he wanted all those things destroyed.
He wanted everything trashed.
Now, is that to whom you reported then?
Yes, sir.
I didn't.
What I did was move myself out of his office.
He had an office in our building, and my office was next to it, of course, like Kunze's and Berner's.
But I took myself out of there and went into the graduate college office where I could take care of the records and moved my clerk who was in the graduate office into my office to take care of
the associate provost when he was there or on the phone or anything.
So I said, you take care of him.
I'm going to take care of the graduate office.
That's the only way I could have operated.
And it worked fine.
But it was difficult.
I was losing my hair.
It was very dramatic.
In those tough times, to whom did you turn for advice?
I called, at one time, I called Dr. Gussman in the office and asked him this particular question I was not sure about.
He told me.
I was fine.
But then when my boss got, found out about it, he came in and chewed me out, told me never to do that again, that I was to come to him with any questions I had.
So I was so tranquilized by then.
I was on tranquilizers.
I was just, okay, he's chewing me out, but it's okay.
And I didn't, I really didn't react because I knew I had to do what I had to do.
And I just overcame it.
Just kept going.
Had no choice.
But everybody was so nice to me.
I must say all the graduate faculty that I dealt with, all the
problems we had, they couldn't have been nicer.
And I was pleased at the way that I did it and they supported me.
So I got that out of it anyway.
Do you remember any goofy things that happened?
Mistakes or snafus?
I can just remember working, you know, just trying to keep my head above water.
And I know I didn't enjoy the office parties because I just couldn't get away from the work.
I just took it with me everywhere I went.
And fortunately, I lived alone, so I didn't.
But I just had to keep going.
But I burned out.
And I've warned people about that that are working like that, that you will eventually burn out.
And then you're no good to anybody.
All right.
Now, looking back over all those years,
If you could award stars of gratitude, to whom would you give the stars?
Oh, I have a lot of people I'm grateful to.
The main person is Dr. Kunze, who was so... Because you must realize, I was not a trained secretary.
Never have been.
But he just made me feel like I was doing great, and I appreciate it, which now I know I wasn't.
But...
He was very understanding and everything so I am most grateful to him and to Mr. Kidd, Professor Kidd, Leo Berner.
This is Harry Kidd?
Yes.
Out of the English?
Yes, Harry Kidd.
What was his...
He was an assistant dean.
He did a lot of Dr. Kudzi's writing or fixed what he wrote.
He never got over his German.

ancestry but he was always willing able to to help I just I have a lot of people all the people I worked with through the colleges very supportive and I seem to be painting this beautiful picture but in that text that that really they were fine people I mean I had no problems with dealing with the people I learned how I learned how to handle people also
Is it correct that in those years this place was much more personal than it would be in the late 80s?
Yes.
Which is fine.
You could work out a lot of things before it ever got to paper.
And that's why we prefer to just work out what you want and then they do the paperwork and then it's fine.
But
It was just a constant battle, simply because there was such quantity.
And we just didn't have enough people to cover it all.
In summary, what were you most proud of in those 25 years?
The fact that I worked for George Coonsey and his goals and his accomplishments during those years, I became a part of it.
A small part of it, but still a part of it.
I was there when it happened and supported him the best I could.
He was a work...
He was a taskmaster.
He worked hard.
He worked harder than we did, but we worked hard.
But he worked harder.
And the last question, what feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M today?
It is my...
It is my family, so to speak.
I feel like I'm a part of this university in some small way, and I care about it tremendously.
I don't think I care any less than some of the former students and people that have belonged here.
Although I was never a student, I really feel
